<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1929-07-24T16:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1929-07-24T16:00:00-05:00" n="104" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d104">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">500.A15a3/78a: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to
                                the Ambassador in Great Britain</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Dawes</hi></persName>)</head>
                        <opener><seg rendition="#center">[Paraphrase]</seg></opener>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1929-07-24T17:00:00-04:00">July 24, 1929—5
                                p.m.</date></dateline></opener>
                        <p>189. President and I are most anxious to have a check-up on accuracy of
                            our figures regarding British cruiser strength as contained in
                            Department’s telegram No. 182, July 21, 7 p.m., before you confer with
                            Gibson and MacDonald on Monday. We find it difficult to make any
                            suggestions or plans until this matter has been cleared up.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Stimson</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>